73	sleeve-gastrectomy	Sleeve gastrectomy	Most common bariatric procedure — 75% of the stomach removed laparoscopically.	6	17	{"root": {"type": "root", "format": "", "indent": 0, "version": 1, "children": [{"type": "paragraph", "format": "", "indent": 0, "version": 1, "children": [{"mode": "normal", "text": "Laparoscopic removal of approximately 75% of the stomach, leaving a banana-shaped tube. Reduces stomach capacity and metabolic appetite signals. The most common bariatric procedure worldwide and our most-recommended primary operation.", "type": "text", "style": "", "detail": 0, "format": 0, "version": 1}], "direction": "ltr", "textFormat": 0}], "direction": "ltr"}}	\N	\N	14800	\N	14800	\N	\N	\N	2026	\N	f	60–90 minutes · general anaesthetic	14 nights on-island; 4–6 weeks to full activity	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	72	2026-05-20 12:55:48.173+00	2026-05-20 12:54:47.535+00	surgical	\N	\N	\N	standard	\N	\N	\N	f	\N
74	roux-en-y-gastric-bypass	Roux-en-Y gastric bypass	Stomach divided and small bowel rerouted — strongest metabolic effect; for severe cases.	6	17	{"root": {"type": "root", "format": "", "indent": 0, "version": 1, "children": [{"type": "paragraph", "format": "", "indent": 0, "version": 1, "children": [{"mode": "normal", "text": "Stomach divided into a small upper pouch and connected directly to the lower small bowel — bypassing the rest of the stomach and upper bowel. Stronger metabolic and weight-loss effect than sleeve, particularly for patients with type-2 diabetes or severe reflux.", "type": "text", "style": "", "detail": 0, "format": 0, "version": 1}], "direction": "ltr", "textFormat": 0}], "direction": "ltr"}}	\N	\N	18400	\N	18400	\N	\N	\N	2026	\N	f	2–3 hours · general anaesthetic	16 nights on-island; 6 weeks to full activity	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	73	2026-05-20 12:55:48.228+00	2026-05-20 12:54:47.558+00	surgical	\N	\N	\N	standard	\N	\N	\N	f	\N
